article.description: Ashley Sweat had 25 points and made the decisive plays down the stretch, helping Kansas State (No. 14 ESPN/USA Today, No. 18 AP) hold off pesky Missouri 58-54 Wednesday night.
article.headline: Kansas State escapes thanks to 25 from Sweat
article.linkText: Sweat's 25 help Kansas State hold off Mizzou
article.story:
MANHATTAN, Kan. -- Ashley Sweat powered into the lane, grabbing an offensive rebound off a missed free throw. Seconds later, she sneaked along the baseline and grabbed another offensive board, sticking it back in for a three-point play.

Two plays, one possession made all the difference in a tight game.

Sweat kept Kansas State close with her shooting and made the decisive plays down the stretch, helping the Wildcats (No. 14 ESPN/USA Today, No. 18 AP) hold off pesky Missouri 58-54 Wednesday night.

"We talk about offensive rebounding all the time," said Sweat, who had six rebounds. "In a situation like that, if you're not crashing offensive rebounds, there's something wrong with you."

Kansas State (19-2, 6-2 Big 12), coming off a 60-50 loss to Iowa State, entered with the nation's best scoring defense at 49.8 points per game, but it was Missouri's defense that dictated the flow of this game.

Collapsing in the lane and racing back out to Kansas State's perimeter shooters, the Tigers (10-11, 1-7) repeatedly forced the Wildcats deep into the shot clock and difficult shots. Kansas State missed many of the open ones, too, shooting 38 percent for the second straight game.

But for all Missouri did to disrupt Kansas State's offensive, it couldn't stop Sweat, particularly with the game on line, resulting in its 13th straight conference road loss and fifth loss overall. Jessra Johnson led the Tigers with 12 points, while Hollins and Bekah Mills added 11 each.

"Obviously, we feel like we let a game slip away," Missouri coach Cindy Stein said. "We let them have some offensive boards where I felt like if we get those boards, we win the game."

Shalin Spani and Marlies Gipson had 11 points each for Kansas State, and Shalee Lehning overcame a tough shooting night -- 1-for-9 -- to finish with eight assists and six rebounds.

The difference, though, was Sweat.

The junior forward helped Kansas State jump out to a big early lead, then kept the Wildcats close when Missouri rallied. With the game on the line, she came up with the biggest plays.

The first came with 1:35 left, when she snared an offensive rebound off a missed free throw by Lehning. Another offensive rebound, this one on a missed 3-pointer by Lehning, came with 59 seconds left and Sweat turned it into a three-point play that put Kansas State up 54-52.

After Sweat grabbed a defensive rebound on a miss by Hollins, Kansas State's Kari Kincaid hit 1 of 2 free throws and Johnson scored on a putback to cut the lead to 55-54. The Tigers fouled Sweat and she calmly hit two free throws with 18 seconds left, then helped harass Mills into a missed layup at the other end.

Gipson provided the final margin by hitting 1 of 2 free throws with 5 seconds left to give Kansas State its 12th straight home win.

"Ashley Sweat, I thought, was just tremendous both on the boards and from the free-throw line," Kansas State coach Deb Patterson said. "She made a lot of big plays and big shots in critical situations and I think that's what separated us a little bit."

Kansas State appeared headed toward a rout after Missouri got off to a miserable start.

Unable to get much of anything inside of 15 feet, the Tigers missed their first seven shots and didn't have a point until Mills scored on a tough runner 6 minutes into the game. Missouri went another 3 minutes before scoring again, falling behind 15-4.

The Tigers kept playing defense, though, forcing Kansas State use most of the shot clock on just about every possession. The Wildcats didn't help themselves by trying to force the ball inside and ended up shooting just 10-of-29 in the first half.

Missouri finally started hitting shots midway through, with Hollins' turnaround triggering a 16-3 run that put the Tigers up 23-20. The Tigers led by three at halftime and kept up the defensive pressure to start the second half, hitting enough shots to keep Kansas State from making a run.

Kansas State finally grabbed the lead at 43-42 on Shalin Spani's 3-pointer with about 8 minutes left, setting up the tight finish.

"I felt like we played well enough to win," Stein said. "But every possession counts in the Big 12. When you play great teams, Kansas State being one of them, every possession counts and we just let a few possessions slip by."
